        Returns:
        The name of the Identifier.

      • setName

        public void setName(java.lang.String name)
        Set the name of the Identifier. Identifier names consist of the following character types: [A-Z, a-z, 0-9, _]. However, cannot start with a number.

        Example inputs include:
        • correctGrammar
        • INCORrect_grammaR_but_123123STILL_workz
        • identifierName4

        Incorrect inputs include:
        • 24JeffGordon (Cannot start an identifier with a number)
        • This.Doesnt_work (Cannot contain a period (or any other punctuation))
        • #omgProgramin (This is not Twitter)
        Parameters:
        name - The String containing the name to set as the identifier.

      • getReturnedNode

        public ValueNode getReturnedNode()
        Get the ValueNode that returns a value if it is used in an expression.

        For example: 
         // Scenario 1
 tree.value.next;
 
 //Scenario 2
 tree;
        In scenario 1, "next" is the returned node because it is the last accessed node. In scenario 2 "tree" is the returned node because it does not access any nodes and is therefore the value that is returned.
        Overrides:
        getReturnedNode in class ValueNode
        Returns:
        The last accessed node, or if the node does not access any nodes, it returns itself.

      • getReferenceNode

        public IdentifierNode getReferenceNode()
        Get the TreeNode that represents the variable that contains the value. For example:
         ClassName obj = new ClassName();
 
 obj.data.methodName();
        In the previous statements, "data" is the reference because the method "methodName()" is being called through the "data" variable.
        Returns:
        The TreeNode that represents the calling variable.

      • getContextNode

        public IdentifierNode getContextNode()
        Get the furthest node that is accessing the specified identifier.

        For example: 
         tree.next.calculateSize()
        In the previous statement, "tree" is the context. If the identifier is not accessed by any other identifiers, then null is returned.
        For example: 
         calculateSize()
        The above would return null.
        Returns:
        The furthest node that accesses the specified identifier.

      • getContextNode

      • getRootAccessNode

        public ValueNode getRootAccessNode()
        Get the furthest node that is accessing the specified identifier.

        For example: 
         tree.next.calculateSize()
        In the previous statement, "tree" is the context. This differs from the getContextNode() call by returning the specified node if the identifier is not accessed by any other identifiers.
        For example: 
         calculateSize()
        The above would return the method call identifier for "calculateSize()".
        Returns:
        The furthest node that accesses the specified identifier.

      • getLastAccessedNode

        public IdentifierNode getLastAccessedNode()
        Get the last node that is accessed by the specified node.

        For example: 
         tree.next.calculateSize()
        In the previous statement, "calculateSize()" is the last accessed node.
        Returns:
        The last node that is accessed by the specified node.

      • getAccessedNode

        public IdentifierNode getAccessedNode()
        Get the next node that is accessed by the specified node.

        For example: 
         tree.next.calculateSize()
        In the previous statement, "calculateSize()" is the accessed node of the "next" node, and "next" is the accessed node of the "tree" node.
        Returns:
        The next node that is accessed by the specified node.
